comment:
"Share of gdp is lower for manufacturing than it was in 2013-14" that doesn't mean manufacturing didn't grow well. It's obvious to everybody it did in absolute terms. The service sector just grew much faster. The economy more than doubled in a decade, so manufacturing also doubled to stay the same %. 
Same thing when you talk about population percentage in manufacturing. India's working population has grown a lot in 10 years, it doesn't mean there aren't more people working in manufacturing today - there are, just that more people are working in other sectors - particularly because the major increase in working population came from agriculture-intense rural population due to higher birth rates. Same issue when you compare India's share in global exports, it depends too much on what happened in other countries. There are too many confounding factors in the data points you're cherrypicking. This is a strange and misleading lens to look at the state of the manufacturing sector in India today. If you were being accurate, you would have atleast shown the absolute numbers at some point which you chose not to.
